I asked them to turn on the volume and told them about my earlier call in but they refused. The bartender then accused us of trying to tell her how to run her bar.  All being said, the hot dogs are good.

One of the absolute best dive bars in Washington DC. They have a fantastic beer and a shot combo for $6. And an amazing sandwich called da beef. It's slightly spicy and lacks cheese, but it has this amazing sauce that makes up for it. They also have phenomenal hot dogs. Fantastic theming, a complete hole in the wall you would never know about otherwise.

No frills Detroit/Chicago bar. Cash only. Great happy hour with $2 Strohs/ $5 Strohs and Bourbon. Only decent Chicago food in the city. Get a dipped Italian beef, Chicago style hot dog, or Italian sausage.
Love the music, the people and service. ONLY CASH :(
Excellent 👍👌

I like this place, but they've ripped me off on drinks multiple times. They don't offer a "well" whiskey, and their "pop" shots are $4 for their cheapest whiskey. I ordered a couple of these for my party, and then I ordered a few $7 "full size" shots. The "full size" $7 shots were the same size as the mini "pop" shots - they even poured into the mini pop glasses. The bar was charging me $3 more per drink for the "pop" option - essentially stealing money from me and lying about drink sizes.

Chicago and Detroit in one place. Coney Dogs and Chicago Dogs in one place. Old Styles and Strohs in one place.  A real dive bar in DC (my favorite). Theres always a game on but it's also a perfect spot to meet up and socialize and rewind from your day or week. Its cash only which is perfect in a world full of plastic. They've got a rooftop with a retractable roof. Best prices I've seen in the city as far as beer and food go. Liquor is a bit high but that's the trade off for everything else being great....  Anyway, it's one of the good ones trust me.
I dig it. Front is a classic dive bar, back room/patio more hip and mod. Only four stars because it's a Cubs and U of Michigan spot. Go White Sox and Brewers and Go Badgers!! Great place.

Nice bar for the area, themed for Midwest America, they nice beers. On the back there is outside sitting area. Food menu is ok. They don't accept credit cards only cash but they have ATM machine onsite.

Great neighborhood bar one of the few places you can get a Chicago hot dog in DC. Try the Old Style(ish) where the"ish" is written on the tap with a sharpie because they could not actually get Old Style beer! But it tastes the same! Great staff. Cash only.

authentic chicago/detroit vibe, food, and drinks. down to earth and very welcoming bartender. a definite must for real midwest folks (and anyone else who appreciates a good time).

The blonde d-bag bartender with a SUPER cooool Bad Saints hat was a pompous a-hole. Never came to the bar to greet us while too busy whispering and joking with his buddies. Then whined like a 8 year old when the 15 people that walked in with us got impatient, “I won’t serve you guys if you’re taking bad about me”. The bar was empty otherwise. Thought he was about to cry for real at one point. He was so offended we came from “Dacha”, even stating loudly. In our group was one of the co-owners of Dacha who recommend we go to Ivy and Coney. He was horrified by the guy. After telling us we had to leave, all 15 of us got up and the bouncer apologized saying, “ I don’t know what’s up with this guy (bartender), he does this all the time. I’m sorry.” Unless this bar fires d-bag Bad Saints bartender and gets a pretentious attitude adjustment I would avoid at all cost. 1 Star is not low enough. Worthless bar that won’t last in DC. A total fad.

We came here while we were in town because we are huge Cubs fans. The bar was really nothing special. There was some Cubs decor but nothing over the top. The drink prices were decent but the atmosphere was lacking. It is cash only and they did have an ATM so that was nice.

Classic American bar. Cheap beer and good company. Menu has everything it needs and nothing that it doesn't. It isn't home, but it's a pleasant reminder of it. Midwest hospitality and grit to spare. I hope they keep things as they are. I'm a fan of the place and will visit again.

Classic dc dive, where you can smoke in the back room if you want.  Food is bleh.  The value is in the experience. Good mix of professionals and drunks and hipsters and regular folk.  Usually a game on the tele.  Its literally among the last of a dying breed.  Get there while it still stands.  Cash only.

Pretty good dive bar. Homesick Chicagoan? Want to make your DC friend do a shot of malort? Only thing off is their giardiniera they use yellow onions in it which gives it an off kinda sweet tangy profile.  Might even taste good to you but it just isn't like giardiniera from home (which shouldn't use any onions). If you do want a jar in DC buying it from Potbelly's is your best bet.

Fantastic neighborhood bar with a large, covered roof deck. They've got a Chicago theme, so if you're into Chicago beer, hot dogs, or sports teams, this is a great hangout. For a while they were allowing people to buy bottles of liquor and store them behind the bar in their name. Not sure if they still do it, but it's a great way to become an instant regular.

The best dive bar in town.

We walked in at 1:30pm, the bar closes at 2pm. There are 5 or 6 guys upstairs, all obviously friends with the bar tender. We only want a couple drinks before turning in for the night. We get one each, and have it gone in a couple minutes. We try to order one more before leaving, we have cash and were going to leave the bartender a $20 tip. He told us no, said they were  closing. It was 1:40. The sign said they closed at 2am, and WHILE he was refusing to serve us another drink WHILE they were still open, he was pouring a shot for one of his friends. I understand that we were the only two out of the total 8 people there that was not wearing a flannel shirt, but the last time I check my wallet full of cash was as good as anyone else's. I'm disappointed that the only place we went to for a late night drink was the only inhospitable place in what was an otherwise fairly welcoming city.

Went to watch a Michigan State basketball game at this Detroit- and Chicago-themed bar. It's a dive, not a sports bar, so understandably there are not many TVs. Of the two TVs in the main room,  one was playing Blackhawk hockey (Chicago themed, I get it) and the other had the NFL (not Detroit or Chicago) which was on at virtually every other place in DC. Bar tenders wouldn't change the station so we left. Disappointed the bar didn't hold up the Detroit side of things. Looked like a cool place, though.

Low-key vibe with very inexpensive beers, nice people, and amazing hot dogs. Great place to watch your Chicago/Detroit sports with fellow fans or just hang out in one of the few remaining neighborhood bars in DC.

Five stars if you are a Chicagoan or Detroiter (or even just a midwesterner) and appreciate a great dive. This place feels like home. The place to watch the Cubs or Tigers. Great for other Chicago or Detroit sports events as well. You're coming here for the beer you drank back home and to cheer and cry with fellow fans.

No frills but excellent service. Went for a late lunch and early beer on a Sunday afternoon. The "roof" is more a room without a ceiling and a lot of windows along one side but good enough to get some sun and fresh air. Food was tasty. Note that the place is cash only. If it were crowded might get cramped and noisy.

First of all, I grew up near Detroit so I was ready and willing to embrace this "Detroit and Chicago bar." But I was not impressed. The only "Detroit" aspects to it are a) they serve (mediocre) Coney dogs, b) they have a mural of Sparky Anderson on the wall, and c) it looks like a riot passed through the place not too long ago. I think they served two Michigan beers (both Bells) and the bartenders acted like they were really too important and busy to be serving you.  They are very much more interested in being a Chicago bar, so I hope they enjoy serving their Chicago patrons. If you want a Michigan bar, go to Kangraoo Boxing Club on 11th.

Visited DC a few weeks ago.  Seems like a bar for regulars and small groups. Drinks are cheeeeap!!! But then again, I'm used to Manhattan ridiculousness. Definitely has a lot of personality in the decor.
This might be my favorite bar in DC. The hot dogs are great, the food and beer is super affordable, and they have free peanuts and a roof deck.

I guess I'll slightly object to some these reviews. This is definitely a dive bar, but it's purposely constructed to feel this way cause this place is only 2 years old. It's cash only, and the upstairs is crowded with no AC. On a hot summer night it can remove some momentum from a bar crawl. I waited 10 minutes alongside an empty bar for the barkeep to return so I can choose from 4 beers.  To be fair everyone I know seems to love this place. It's just not for me.
I feel like I'm back in Chicago!  All of the classic drinks and dogs of the midwest.  Lots of smoke, though.
Awesome Detroit & Chicago Bar. Great Hot dogs made to order. They have a MAME Machine for all you gamers. Great Beers on tap.

A cool new spot in Shaw. It has a bit of a "work in progress" vibe to it, but I think it adds to the atmosphere. A great quiet spot to go have a beer and be able to talk to the people you are with. They have food, but it didn't seem terribly impressive to me. Fine for bar bites, not great for dinner.

Ivy and Coney is a sports bar.... but a sports bar that is a step away from being a dive bar. Both fine types of establishments in their own rights, but I just wish that Ivy and Coney would stop calling themselves a sports bar because they are just barely that.  They have television and a few sport memorabilia on the walls but everything else screams dive bar. The dark lighting, the small area the whole bar takes, the quality of food, the type of local neighborhood people that frequent it, all of it says dive bar.  They have a modest selection of beer and a some easy to make food that does the job, they are not gourmet quality, but they fill you up. Come here for a quick drink and maybe a hotdog but don't expect to watch a big game here and have a great experience.
Perfect neighborhood bar. Authentic Chicago Dogs. Just the right size for a Monday night beer.

With a slight nod to speakeasies, you'll probably walk right past it once or twice before figuring out where it is.  Watch for the green door- when you spot the venue's name on the door you'll kick yourself for walking past it (well... or pedantically boast at how you got it on the first try).  Good prices and OK enough food -- a local spot I can get a hot dog when so-craving (especially since DC-3 is so far away by Eastern Market).
Carefully hidden Chicago/Detroit style cash only sports bar with beer and ballpark style hotdogs.

Come here if you are craving a taste of the Midwest. Bar celebrates Chicago & Detroit. They fly in the ingredients for the Chicago dog - this is the real deal. Bring cash and play some Mario Kart with friends in the back room.
